  This paper develops a novel weak multilevel Monte-Carlo (MLMC) approximation
scheme for L\'evy-driven Stochastic Differential Equations (SDEs). The scheme
is based on the state space discretization (via a continuous-time Markov chain
approximation) of the pure-jump component of the driving L\'evy process and is
particularly suited if the multidimensional driver is given by a L\'evy copula.
The multilevel version of the algorithm requires a new coupling of the
approximate L\'evy drivers in the consecutive levels of the scheme, which is
defined via a coupling of the corresponding Poisson point processes. The
multilevel scheme is weak in the sense that the bound on the level variances is
based on the coupling alone without requiring strong convergence. Moreover, the
coupling is natural for the proposed discretization of jumps and is easy to
simulate. The approximation scheme and its multilevel analogous are applied to
examples taken from mathematical finance, including the pricing of credit,
equity and interest rate derivatives.
